<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading"><span class=3D"ez-toc-section" id=3D"awg-and=
-mm%c2%b2-whats-the-difference"></span>AWG AND mm=C2=B2: WHAT=E2=80=99S THE=
 DIFFERENCE?<span class=3D"ez-toc-section-end"></span></h2>



<p>Before we jump to the conversion, it=E2=80=99s crucial to understand the=
 core difference between these two units:</p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li><strong>AWG (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_wire_gau=
ge" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener">American Wire Gauge</a>)<=
/strong>: Used primarily in the US, Canada, and other North American countr=
ies. This standard, governed by <strong>ASTM B 496</strong> and ASTM <stron=
g>B 400,</strong> is a logarithmic scale where a higher AWG number denotes =
a thinner wire. For example, a 22 AWG wire is much thinner than a 10 AWG wi=
re.</li>



<li><strong>mm=C2=B2 (Square Millimeters)</strong>:&nbsp;Used throughout mo=
st of the world that employs the metric system. This standard, defined by&n=
bsp;<strong>IEC 60228</strong>, is a direct measurement of the conductor=E2=
=80=99s<strong>&nbsp;cross-sectional area</strong>. A larger mm=C2=B2 value=
 means a thicker, more robust cable.</li>
</ul>



<p><strong>Key Takeaway:</strong>&nbsp;The fundamental difference lies in t=
heir nature: AWG is a&nbsp;<em>gauge number</em>&nbsp;based on a logarithmi=
c scale, while mm=C2=B2 is a direct measurement of the&nbsp;<em>physical cr=
oss-sectional area</em>.</p>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading"><span class=3D"ez-toc-section" id=3D"why-cor=
rect-cable-sizing-is-critical"></span>WHY CORRECT CABLE SIZING IS CRITICAL<=
span class=3D"ez-toc-section-end"></span></h2>



<p>Choosing the correct cable size is paramount for safety, performance, an=
d cost-efficiency. A thin cable has higher electrical resistance, which lea=
ds to voltage drop and excessive heat generation under load. This can cause=
 inefficiency, damage to insulation, and in severe cases, fire. Conversely,=
 a thicker cable has lower resistance and can safely carry higher currents.=
</p>



<blockquote class=3D"wp-block-quote is-layout-flow wp-block-quote-is-layout=
-flow">
<p><strong>Tip</strong>:&nbsp;Always overspecify slightly when in doubt. A =
cable with a larger cross-section (lower AWG / higher mm=C2=B2) than strict=
ly necessary provides a safety margin and reduces energy losses.</p>
</blockquote>



